docs.abstract: Egyptian security officials raided the home of a well-known activist early Wednesday, the latest arrest in a wave of post-election repression.
docs.snippet: Egyptian security officials raided the home of a well-known activist early Wednesday, the latest arrest in a wave of post-election repression.
docs.lead_paragraph: CAIRO — For the past decade, Wael Abbas has been a fierce critic of Egypt’s authoritarian leaders, using YouTube to highlight police torture, and building up a huge Twitter following that he used to draw attention to the plight of dissidents who had vanished into state custody.

headline.main: As Sisi Silences Critics, Hopes Fade That Egypt’s Crackdown Will Ease
headline.print_headline: Across Egypt, Crackdown On Dissent Continues

docs.abstract: For Rudolph Giuliani, getting booed in a place he was once revered was not just a personal slight, but a sign of how much he and the city he once ran have parted ways.
docs.snippet: For Rudolph Giuliani, getting booed in a place he was once revered was not just a personal slight, but a sign of how much he and the city he once ran have parted ways.
docs.lead_paragraph: The boos cascaded from the stands, wafting over Monument Park, turning a moment of between-inning indifference at Yankee Stadium into a visceral spirit cleansing.

headline.main: For Giuliani (Boo!), Yankee Stadium Is No Longer a Safe Space
headline.print_headline: Giuliani, Booed at Yankee Stadium, Loses His Home-Field Advantage

docs.abstract: There is no such thing as the P.C. police.
docs.snippet: There is no such thing as the P.C. police.
docs.lead_paragraph: On Tuesday, ABC canceled its “Roseanne” revival, the network’s first No. 1 show in 24 years, after its star Roseanne Barr referred to Valerie Jarrett, a former senior adviser to President Barack Obama, as the offspring of the “Muslim Brotherhood & Planet of the Apes.”

headline.main: Roseanne Barr’s Right to Offend and Our Right to Say No
headline.print_headline: Our Right to Say No to ‘Roseanne’

docs.abstract: Heartbeat Opera is presenting a new version that updates its setting, employs a largely nonwhite cast and features Midwestern prison choirs.
docs.snippet: Heartbeat Opera is presenting a new version that updates its setting, employs a largely nonwhite cast and features Midwestern prison choirs.
docs.lead_paragraph: Few opera choruses are as moving as the one a group of prisoners sings in Act I of Beethoven’s “Fidelio.” Released temporarily from their cells, the inmates almost whisper a hymnlike paean to liberty: “Oh, what a joy to breathe freely again in the open air.”
